at there might be a search in the room, and that the clothes might betray me. I threw open the window, reopening by my violence a small cut which I had inflicted upon myself in the bedroom that morning. Then I seized my coat, which was weighted by the coppers which I had just transferred to it from the leather bag in which I carried my takings. I hurled it out of the window, and it disappeared into the Thames. The other clothes would have followed, but at that moment there was a rush of constables up the stair, and a few minutes after I found, rather, I confess, to my relief, that instead of being identified as Mr. Neville St. Clair, I was arrested as his murderer.\a147I do not know that there is anything else for me to explain. I was determined to preserve my disguise as long as possible, and hence my preference for a dirty face. Knowing that my wife would be terribly anxious, I slipped off my ring and confided it to the Lascar at a moment when no constable was watching me, together with a hurried scrawl, telling her that she had no cause to fear.\a148\a147That note only reached her yesterday,\a148 said Holmes.\a147Good God! What a week she must have spent!\a148\a147The police have watched this Lascar,\a148 said Inspector Bradstreet, \a147and I can quite understand that he might find it difficult to post a letter unobserved. Probably he handed it to some sailor customer of his, who forgot all about it for some days.\a148\a147That was it,\a148 said Holmes, nodding approvingly; \a147I have no doubt of it. But have you never been prosecuted for begging?\a148\a147Many times; but what was a fine to me?\a148\a147It must stop here, however,\a148 said Bradstreet. \a147If the police are to hush this thing up, there must be no more of Hugh Boone.\a148\a147I have sworn it by the most solemn oaths which a man can take.\a148\a147In that case I think that it is probable that no further steps may be taken. But if you are found again, then all must come out. I am