ng which Holmes leaned his chin upon his hands and stared into the crackling fire.\a147This is a very deep business,\a148 he said at last. \a147There are a thousand details which I should desire to know before I decide upon our course of action. Yet we have not a moment to lose. If we were to come to Stoke Moran to-day, would it be possible for us to see over these rooms without the knowledge of your stepfather?\a148\a147As it happens, he spoke of coming into town to-day upon some most important business. It is probable that he will be away all day, and that there would be nothing to disturb you. We have a housekeeper now, but she is old and foolish, and I could easily get her out of the way.\a148\a147Excellent. You are not averse to this trip, Watson?\a148\a147By no means.\a148\a147Then we shall both come. What are you going to do yourself?\a148\a147I have one or two things which I would wish to do now that I am in town. But I shall return by the twelve o\a146clock train, so as to be there in time for your coming.\a148 \a147And you may expect us early in the afternoon. I have myself some small business matters to attend to. Will you not wait and breakfast?\a148\a147No, I must go. My heart is lightened already since I have confided my trouble to you. I shall look forward to seeing you again this afternoon.\a148 She dropped her thick black veil over her face and glided from the room.\a147And what do you think of it all, Watson?\a148 asked Sherlock Holmes, leaning back in his chair.\a147It seems to me to be a most dark and sinister business.\a148\a147Dark enough and sinister enough.\a148\a147Yet if the lady is correct in saying that the flooring and walls are sound, and that the door, window, and chimney are impassable, then her sister must have been undoubtedly alone when she met her mysterious end.\a148\a147What becomes, then, of these nocturnal whistles, and what of the very peculiar words of the dying woman?\a148\a147I cannot think.\a148