versation. Again and again I had to ask him whether he would give in and sign the documents. Again and again I had the same indignant reply. But soon a happy thought came to me. I took to adding on little sentences of my own to each question, innocent ones at first, to test whether either of our companions knew anything of the matter, and then, as I found that they showed no signs I played a more dangerous game. Our conversation ran something like this:\a147\a160\a145You can do no good by this obstinacy. \iWho are you\i?\a146\a147\a160\a145I care not. \iI am a stranger in London\i.\a146\a147\a160\a145Your fate will be upon your own head. \iHow long have you been here?\i\a146\a147\a160\a145Let it be so. \iThree weeks\i.\a146\a147\a160\a145The property can never be yours. \iWhat ails you?\i\a146\a147\a160\a145It shall not go to villains. \iThey are starving me\i.\a146\a147\a160\a145You shall go free if you sign. \iWhat house is this?\i\a146\a147\a160\a145I will never sign. \iI do not know\i.\a146\a147\a160\a145You are not doing her any service. \i What is your name?\i\a146\a147\a160\a145Let me hear her say so. \iKratides\i.\a146\a147\a160\a145You shall see her if you sign. \iWhere are you from?\i\a146\a147\a160\a145Then I shall never see her. \iAthens\i.\a146\a147Another five minutes, Mr. Holmes, and I should have wormed out the whole story under their very noses. My very next question might have cleared the matter up, but at that instant the door opened and a woman stepped into the room. I could not see her clearly enough to know more than that she was tall and graceful, with black hair, and clad in some sort of loose white gown.\a147\a160\a145Harold,\a146 said she, speaking English with a broken accent. \a145I could not stay away longer. It is so lonely up there with only\a151 Oh, my God, it is Paul!\a146\a147These last words were in Greek, and at the same instant the man with a convulsive effort tore the plaster from his lips, and scre