 house, or immediately outside the house, if to break it was his sole object.\a148\a147He was rattled and bustled by meeting this other fellow. He hardly knew what he was doing.\a148\a147Well, that\a146s likely enough. But I wish to call your attention very particularly to the position of this house in the garden of which the bust was destroyed.\a148Lestrade looked about him.\a147It was an empty house, and so he knew that he would not be disturbed in the garden.\a148\a147Yes, but there is another empty house farther up the street which he must have passed before he came to this one. Why did he not break it there, since it is evident that every yard that he carried it increased the risk of someone meeting him?\a148\a147I give it up,\a148 said Lestrade.Holmes pointed to the street lamp above our heads.\a147He could see what he was doing here and he could not there. That was his reason.\a148\a147By Jove! that\a146s true,\a148 said the detective. \a147Now that I come to think of it, Dr. Barnicot\a146s bust was broken not far from his red lamp. Well, Mr. Holmes, what are we to do with that fact?\a148\a147To remember it\a151 to docket it. We may come on something later which will bear upon it. What steps do you propose to take now, Lestrade?\a148\a147The most practical way of getting at it, in my opinion, is to identify the dead man. There should be no difficulty about that. When we have found who he is and who his associates are, we should have a good start in learning what he was doing in Pitt Street last night, and who it was who met him and killed him on the doorstep of Mr. Horace Harker. Don\a146t you think so?\a148\a147No doubt; and yet it is not quite the way in which I should approach the case.\a148\a147What would you do, then?\a148\a147Oh, you must not let me influence you in any way. I suggest that you go on your line and I on mine. We can compare notes afterwards, and each will supplement the other.\a148\a147Very good,\a148 said Le