a147You will tell him exactly how you have left me,\a148 said he. \a147You will convey the very impression which is in your own mind\a151 a dying man\a151 a dying and delirious man. Indeed, I cannot think why the whole bed of the ocean is not one solid mass of oysters, so prolific the creatures seem. Ah, I am wandering! Strange how the brain controls the brain! What was I saying, Watson?\a148\a147My directions for Mr. Culverton Smith.\a148\a147Ah, yes, I remember. My life depends upon it. Plead with him, Watson. There is no good feeling between us. His nephew, Watson\a151 I had suspicions of foul play and I allowed him to see it. The boy died horribly. He has a grudge against me. You will soften him, Watson. Beg him, pray him, get him here by any means. He can save me\a151 only he!\a148\a147I will bring him in a cab, if I have to carry him down to it.\a148\a147You will do nothing of the sort. You will persuade him to come. And then you will return in front of him. Make any excuse so as not to come with him. Don\a146t forget, Watson. You won\a146t fail me. You never did fail me. No doubt there are natural enemies which limit the increase of the creatures. You and I, Watson, we have done our part. Shall the world, then, be overrun by oysters? No, no; horrible! You\a146ll convey all that is in your mind.\a148I left him full of the image of this magnificent intellect babbling like a foolish child. He had handed me the key, and with a happy thought I took it with me lest he should lock himself in. Mrs. Hudson was waiting, trembling and weeping, in the passage. Behind me as I passed from the flat I heard Holmes\a146s high, thin voice in some delirious chant. Below, as I stood whistling for a cab, a man came on me through the fog.\a147How is Mr. Holmes, sir?\a148 he asked.It was an old acquaintance, Inspector Morton, of Scotland Yard, dressed in unofficial tweeds.\a147He is very ill,\a148 I answered.He looked at me in a most singular fashion. Had it not been too fiendish, I could have imagined that the gleam of the fanlight showed exultation in his face.\a147I heard some rumour of it,\a148 said he.The cab had driven up, and I left him.Lower Burke Street proved to be a line of fine houses lying in the vague borderland between Notting Hill and Kensington. The particular one at which my cabman pulled up had an air of smug and demure respectability in its old-fashioned iron railings, its massive folding-door, and its shining brasswork. All was in keeping with a solemn butler who appeared framed in the pink radiance of a tinted electric light behind him.\a147Yes, Mr. Culverton Smith is in. Dr. Watson! Very good, sir, I will take up your card.\a148My humble name and title did not appear to impress Mr. Culverton Smith. Through the half-open door I heard a high, petulant, penetrating voice.\a147Who is this person? What does he want? Dear me, Staples, how often have I said that I am not to be disturbed in my hours of study?\a148There came a gentle flow of soothing explanation from the butler.\a147Well, I won\a146t see him, Staples. I can\a146t have my work interrupted like this. I am not at home. Say so. Tell him to come in the morning if he really must see me.\a148Again the gentle murmur.\a147Well, well, give him that message. He can come in the morning, or he can stay away. My work must not be hindered.\a148I thought of Holmes tossing upon his bed of sickness and counting the minutes, perhaps, until I could bring help to him. It was not a time to stand upon ceremony. His life depended upon my promptness. Before the apologetic butler had delivered his message I had pushed past him and was in the room.With a shrill cry of anger a man rose from a reclining chair beside the fire. I saw a great yellow face, coarse-grained and greasy, with heavy, double-chin, and two sullen, menacing grey eyes which glared at me from under tufted and sandy brows. A high bald head had a small velvet smoking-cap poised coqu