ol beside her.\a147That is Martha, the only servant I have left.\a148The secretary chuckled.\a147She might almost personify Britannia,\a148 said he, \a147with her complete self-absorption and general air of comfortable somnolence. Well, \iau revoir\i, Von Bork!\a148 With a final wave of his hand he sprang into the car, and a moment later the two golden cones from the headlights shot forward through the darkness. The secretary lay back in the cushions of the luxurious limousine, with his thoughts so full of the impending European tragedy that he hardly observed that as his car swung round the village street it nearly passed over a little Ford coming in the opposite direction.Von Bork walked slowly back to the study when the last gleams of the motor lamps had faded into the distance. As he passed he observed that his old housekeeper had put out her lamp and retired. It was a new experience to him, the silence and darkness of his widespread house, for his family and household had been a large one. It was a relief to him, however, to think that they were all in safety and that, but for that one old woman who had lingered in the kitchen, he had the whole place to himself. There was a good deal of tidying up to do inside his study and he set himself to do it until his keen, handsome face was flushed with the heat of the burning papers. A leather valise stood beside his table, and into this he began to pack very neatly and systematically the precious contents of his safe. He had hardly got started with the work, however, when his quick ears caught the sound of a distant car. Instantly he gave an exclamation of satisfaction, strapped up the valise, shut the safe, locked it, and hurried out on to the terrace. He was just in time to see the lights of a small car come to a halt at the gate. A passenger sprang out of it and advanced swiftly towards him, while the chauffeur, a heavily built, elderly man with a grey moustache, settled down like one who resigns himself to a long vigil.\a147Well?\a148 asked Von Bork eagerly, running forward to meet his visitor.For answer the man waved a small brown-paper parcel triumphantly above his head.\a147You can give me the glad hand to-night, mister,\a148 he cried. \a147I\a146m bringing home the bacon at last.\a148\a147The signals?\a148\a147Same as I said in my cable. Every last one of them, semaphore, lamp code, Marconi\a151 a copy, mind you, not the original. That was too dangerous. But it\a146s the real goods, and you can lay to that.\a148 He slapped the German upon the shoulder with a rough familiarity from which the other winced.\a147Come in,\a148 he said. \a147I\a146m all alone in the house. I was only waiting for this. Of course a copy is better than the original. If an original were missing they would change the whole thing. You think it\a146s all safe about the copy?\a148The Irish-American had entered the study and stretched his long limbs from the armchair. He was a tall, gaunt man of sixty, with clear-cut features and a small goatee beard which gave him a general resemblance to the caricatures of Uncle Sam. A half-smoked, sodden cigar hung from the corner of his mouth, and as he sat down he struck a match and relit it. \a147Making ready for a move?\a148 he remarked as he looked round him. \a147Say, mister,\a148 he added, as his eyes fell upon the safe from which the curtain was now removed, \a147you don\a146t tell me you keep your papers in that?\a148\a147Why not?\a148\a147Gosh, in a wide-open contraption like that! And they reckon you to be some spy. Why, a Yankee crook would be into that with a can-opener. If I\a146d known that any letter of mine was goin\a146 to lie loose in a thing like that I\a146d have been a mug to write to you at all.\a148\a147It would puzzle any crook to force that safe,\a148 Von Bork answered. \a147You won\a146t cut that metal with any tool.\a148\a147But the lock?\a148\a147No, it\a146s a double combination lock. You know what that is?\a148\a147Search me,\a148 said the American.\a147Well, you need a word as well as a set of figures before you can get the lock to work.\a148 He rose and showed a double-radiating disc round the keyhole. \a147This outer one is for the letters, the inner one for the figures.\a148\a147Well, well, that\a146s fine.\a148\a147So it\a146s not quite as simple as you thought. It was four years ago that I had it made, and what do you think I chose for the word and figures?\a148\a147It\a146s beyond me.\a148\a147Well, I chose August for the word, and 1914 for the figures, and here we are.\a148The American\a146s face showed his surprise and admiration.\a147My, but that was smart! You had it down to a fine thing.\a148\a147Yes, a few of us even then could have guessed the date. Here it is, and I\a146m shutting down to-morrow morning. \a148\a147Well, I guess you\a146ll have to fix me up also. I\a146m not staying in this goldarned country all on my lonesome. In a week or less, from what I see, John Bull will be on his hind legs and fair ramping. I\a146d rather watch him from over the water.\a148\a147But you\a146re an American citizen?\a148\a147Well, so was Jack James an American citizen, but he\a146s doing time in Portland all the same. It cuts no ice with a British copper to tell him you\a146re an American citizen. \a145It\a146s British law and order over here,\a146 says he. By the way, mister, talking of Jack James, it seems to me you don\a146t do much to cover your men.\a148\a147What do you mean?\a148 Von Bork asked sharply.\a147Well, you are their employer, ain\a146t you? It\a146s up to you to see that they don\a146t fall down. But they do fall down, and when did you ever pick them up? There\a146s James\a151\a148\a147It was James\a146s own fault. You know that yourself. He was too self-willed for the job.\a148\a147James was a bonehead\a151 I give you that. Then there was Hollis. \a148\a147The man was mad.\a148\a147Well, he went a bit woozy towards the end. It\a146s enough to make a man bughouse when he has to play a part from morning to night with a hundred guys all ready to set the coppers wise to him. But now there is Steiner\a151\a148Von Bork started violently, and his ruddy face turned a shade paler.\a147What about Steiner?\a148\a147Well, they\a146ve got him, that\a146s all. They raided his store last night, and he and his papers are all in Portsmouth jail. You\a146ll go off and he, poor devil, will have to stand the racket, and lucky if he gets off with his life. That\a146s why I want to get over the water as soon as you do.\a148Von Bork was a strong, self-contained man, but it was easy to see that the news had shaken him.\a147How could they have got on to Steiner?\a148 he muttered. \a147That\a146s the worst blow yet.\a148\a147Well, you nearly had a worse one, for I believe they are not far off me.\a148\a147You don\a146t mean that!\a148\a147Sure thing. My landlady down Fratton way had some inquiries, and when I heard of it I guessed it was time for me to hustle. But what I want to know, mister, is how the coppers know these things? Steiner is the fifth man you\a146ve lost since I signed on with you, and I know the name of the sixth if I don\a146t get a move on. How do you explain it, and ain\a146t you ashamed to see your men go down like this?\a148Von Bork flushed crimson.\a147How dare you speak in such a way!\a148\a147If I didn\a146t dare things, mister, I wouldn\a146t be in your service. But I\a146ll tell you straight what is in my mind. I\a146ve heard that with you German politicians when an agent has done his work you are not sorry to see him put away.\a148Von Bork sprang to his feet.\a147Do you dare to suggest that I have given away my own agents!\a148\a147I don\a146t stand for that, mister, but there\a146s a stool pigeon or a cross somewhere, and it\a146s up to you to find out where it is. Anyhow I am taking no more chances. It\a146s me for little Holland, and the sooner the better.\a148Von Bork had mastered his anger.\a147We have been allies too long to quarrel now at the very hour of victory,\a148 he said. \a147You\a146ve done splendid work and taken risks, and I can\a146t forget it. By all means go to Holland, and you can get a boat from Rotterdam to New York. No other line will be safe a week from now. I\a146ll take that book and pack it with the rest.\a148The American held the small parcel in his hand, but made no motion to give it up.\a147What about the dough?\a148 he asked.\a147The what?\a148\a147The boodle. The reward. The 500 pounds. The gunner turned damned nasty at the last, and I had to square him with an extra hundred dollars or it would have been nitsky for you and me. \a145Nothin\a146 doin\a146!\a146 says he, and he meant it, too, but the last hundred did it. It\a146s cost me two hundred pound from first to last, so it isn\a146t likely I\a146d give it up without gettin\a146 my wad. \a148Von Bork smiled with some bitterness. \a147You don\a146t seem to have a very high opinion of my honour,\a148 said he, \a147you want the money before you give up the book.\a148\a147Well, mister, it is a business proposition.\a148\a147All right. Have your way.\a148 He sat down at the table and scribbled a cheque, which he tore from the book, but he refrained from handing it to his companion. \a147After all, since we are to be on such terms, Mr. Altamont,\a148 said he, \a147I don\a146t see why I should trust you any more than you trust me. Do you understand?\a148 he added, looking back over his shoulder at the American. \a147There\a146s the cheque upon the table. I claim the right to examine that parcel before you pick the money up.\a148The American passed it over without a word. Von Bork undid a winding of string and two wrappers of paper. Then he sat gazing for a moment in silent amazement at a small blue book which lay before him. Across the cover was printed in golden letters \iPractical Handbook of Bee Culture\i. Only for one instant did the master spy glare at this strangely irrelevant inscription. The next he was gripped at the back of his neck by a grasp of iron, and a chloroformed sponge was held in front of his writhing face.\a147Another glass, Watson!\a148 said Mr. Sherlock Holmes as he extended the bottle of Imperial Tokay.The thickset chauffeur, who had seated himself by the table pushed forward his glass with some eagerness.\a147It is a good wine, Holmes.\a148\a147A remarkable wine, Watson. Our friend upon the sofa has assured me that it is from Franz Josef\a146s special cellar at the Schoenbrunn Palace. Might I trouble you to open the window for chloroform vapour does not help the palate.\a148The safe was ajar, and Holmes standing in front of it was removing \idossier\i after \idossier\i, swiftly examining each, and then packing it neatly in Von Bork\a146s valise. The German lay upon the sofa sleeping stertorously with a strap round his upper arms and another round his legs. \a147We need not hurry ourselves, Watson. We are safe from interruption. Would you mind touching the bell? There is no one in the house except old Martha, who has played her part to admiration. I got her the situation here when first I took the matter up. Ah, Martha, you will be glad to hear that all is well.\a148The pleasant old lady had appeared in the doorway. She curtseyed with a smile to Mr. Holmes, but glanced with some apprehension at the figure upon the sofa.\a147It is all right, Martha. He has not been hurt at all.\a148\a147I am glad of that, Mr. Holmes. According to his lights he has been a kind master. He wanted me to go with his wife to Germany yesterday, but that would hardly have suited your plans, would it, sir?\a148\a147No, indeed, Martha. So long as you were here I was easy in my mind. We waited some time for your signal to-night.\a148\a147It was the secretary, sir.\a148\a147I know. His car passed ours.\a148\a147I thought he would never go. I knew that it would not suit your plans, sir, to find him here.\a148\a147No, indeed. Well, it only meant that we waited half an hour or so until I saw your lamp go out and knew that the coast was clear. You can report to me to-morrow in London, Martha, at Claridge\a146s Hotel.\a148\a147Very good, sir.\a148\a147I suppose you have everything ready to leave.\a148\a147Yes, sir. He posted seven letters to-day. I have the addresses as usual.\a148\a147Very good, Martha. I will look into them to-morrow. Goodnight. These papers,\a148 he continued as the old lady vanished, \a147are not of very great importance, for, of course, the information which they represent has been sent off long ago to the German government. These are the originals which could not safely be got out of the country.\a148\a147Then they are of no use.\a148\a147I should not go so far as to say that, Watson. They will at least show our people what is known and what is not. I may say that a good many of these papers have come through me, and I need not add are thoroughly untrustworthy. It would brighten my declining years to see a German cruiser navigating the Solent according to the mine-field plans which I have furnished. But you, Watson\a148he stopped his work and took his old friend by the shoulders\a147I\a146ve hardly seen you in the light yet. How have the years used you? You look the same blithe boy as ever. \a148\a147I feel twenty years younger, Holmes. I have seldom felt so happy as when I got your wire asking me to meet you at Harwich with the car. But you, Holmes\a151 you have changed very little\a151 save for that horrible goatee.\a148\a147These are the sacrifices one makes for one\a146s country, Watson,\a148 said Holmes, pulling at his little tuft. \a147To-morrow it will be but a dreadful memory. With my hair cut and a few other superficial changes I shall no doubt reappear at Claridge\a146s tomorrow as I was before this American stunt\a151 I beg your pardon, Watson, my well of English seems to be permanently defiled\a151 before this American job came my way.\a148\a147But you have retired, Holmes. We heard of you as living the life of a hermit among your bees and your books in a small farm upon the South Downs.\a148\a147Exactly, Watson. Here is the fruit of my leisured ease, the \imagnum opus\i of my latter years!\a148 He picked up the volume from the table and read out the whole title, \iPractical Handbook of Bee Culture, with Some Observations upon the Segregation of the Queen\i. \a147Alone I did it. Behold the fruit of pensive nights and laborious days when I watched the little working gangs as once I watched the criminal world of London.\a148\a147But how did you get to work again?\a148\a147Ah, I have often marvelled at it myself. The Foreign Minister alone I could have withstood, but when the Premier also deigned to visit my humble roof! The fact is, Watson, that this gentleman upon the sofa was a bit too good for our people. He was in a class by himself. Things were going wrong, and no one could understand why they were going wrong. Agents were suspected or even caught, but there was evidence of some strong and secret central force. It was absolutely necessary to expose it. Strong pressure was brought upon me to look into the matter. It has cost me two years, Watson, but they have not been devoid of excitement. When I say that I started my pilgrimage at Chicago, graduated in an Irish secret society at Buffalo, gave serious trouble to the constabulary at Skibbareen, and so eventually caught the eye of a subordinate agent of Von Bork, who recommended me as a likely man, you will realize that the matter was complex. Since then I have been honoured by his confidence, which has not prevented most of his plans going subtly wrong and five of his best agents being in prison. I watched them, Watson, and I picked them as they ripened. Well, sir, I hope that you are none the worse!\a148The last remark was addressed to Von Bork himself, who after much gasping and blinking had lain quietly listening to Holmes\a146s statement. He broke out now into a furious stream of German invective, his face convulsed with passion. Holmes continued his swift investigation of documents while his prisoner cursed and swore.\a147Though unmusical, German is the most expressive of all languages,\a148 he observed when Von Bork had stopped from pure exhaustion. \a147Hullo! Hullo!\a148 he added as he looked hard at the corner of a tracing before putting it in the box. \a147This should put another bird in the cage. I had no idea that the paymaster was such a rascal, though I have long had an eye upon him. Mister Von Bork, you have a great deal to answer for.\a148The prisoner had raised himself with some difficulty upon the sofa and was staring with a strange mixture of amazement and hatred at his captor. I shall get level with you, Altamont,\a148 he said, speaking with slow deliberation. \a147If it takes me all my life I shall get level with you!\a148\a147The old sweet song,\a148 said Holmes. \a147How often have I heard it in days gone by. It was a favourite ditty of the late lamented Professor Moriarty. Colonel Sebastian Moran has also been known to warble it. And yet I live and keep bees upon the South Downs.\a148\a147Curse you, you double traitor!\a148 cried the German, straining against his bonds and glaring murder from his furious eyes.\a147No, no, it is not so bad as that,\a148 said Holmes, smiling. \a147As my speech surely shows you, Mr. Altamont of Chicago had no existence in fact. I used him and he is gone.\a148\a147Then who are you?\a148\a147It is really immaterial who I am, but since the matter seems to interest you, Mr. Von Bork, I may say that this is not my first acquaintance with the members of your family. I have done a good deal of business in Germany in the past and my name is probably familiar to you.\a148\a147I would wish to know it,\a148 said the Prussian grimly.\a147It was I who brought about the separation between Irene Adler and the late King of Bohemia when your cousin Heinrich was the Imperial Envoy. It was I also who saved from murder, by the Nihilist Klopman, Count Von und Zu Grafenstein, who was your mother\a146s elder brother. It was I\a151\a148Von Bork sat up in amazement.\a147There is only one man,\a148 he cried.\a147Exactly,\a148 said Holmes.Von Bork groaned and sank back on the sofa. \a147And most of that information came through you,\a148 he cried. \a147What is it worth? What have I done? It is my ruin forever!\a148\a147It is certainly a little untrustworthy,\a148 said Holmes. \a147It will require some checking and you have little time to check it. Your admiral may find the new guns rather larger than he expects, and the cruisers perhaps a trifle faster.\a148Von Bork clutched at his own throat in despair.\a147There are a good many other points of detail which will, no doubt, come to light in good time. But you have one quality which is very rare in a German, Mr. Von Bork: you are a sportsman and you will bear me no ill-will when you realize that you, who have outwitted so many other people, have at last been outwitted yourself. After all, you have done your best for your country, and I have done my best for mine, and what could be more natural? Besides,\a148 he added, not unkindly, as he laid his hand upon the shoulder of the prostrate man, \a147it is better than to fall before some more ignoble foe. These papers are now ready. Watson. If you will help me with our prisoner, I think that we may get started for London at once.\a148It was no easy task to move Von Bork, for he was a strong and a desperate man. Finally, holding either arm, the two friends walked him very slowly down the garden walk which he had trod with such proud confidence when he received the congratulations of the famous diplomatist only a few hours before. After a short, final struggle he was hoisted, still bound hand and foot, into the spare seat of the little car. His precious valise was wedged in beside him.\a147I trust that you are as comfortable as circumstances permit,\a148 said Holmes when the final arrangements were made. \a147Should I be guilty of a liberty if I lit a cigar and placed it between your lips?\a148But all amenities were wasted upon the angry German.\a147I suppose you realize, Mr. Sherlock Holmes,\a148 said he, \a147that if your government bears you out in this treatment it becomes an act of war.\a148\a147What about your government and all this treatment?\a148 said Holmes, tapping the valise.\a147You are a private individual. You have no warrant for my arrest. The whole proceeding is absolutely illegal and outrageous.\a148\a147Absolutely,\a148 said Holmes.\a147Kidnapping a German subject.\a148\a147And stealing his private papers.\a148\a147Well, you realize your position, you and your accomplice here. If I were to shout for help as we pass through the village\a151\a148\a147My dear sir, if you did anything so foolish you would probably enlarge the two limited titles of our village inns by giving us \a145The Dangling Prussian\a146 as a signpost. The Englishman is a patient creature, but at present his temper is a little inflamed, and it would be as well not to try him too far. No, Mr. Von Bork, you will go with us in a quiet, sensible fashion to Scotland Yard, whence you can send for your friend, Baron Von Herling, and see if even now you may not fill that place which he has reserved for you in the ambassadorial suite. As to you, Watson, you are joining us with your old service, as I understand, so London won\a146t be out of your way. Stand with me here upon the terrace, for it may be the last quiet talk that we shall ever have.\a148The two friends chatted in intimate converse for a few minutes, recalling once again the days of the past, while their prisoner vainly wriggled to undo the bonds that held him. As they turned to the car Holmes pointed back to the moonlit sea and shook a thoughtful head.\a147There\a146s an east wind coming, Watson.\a148\a147I think not, Holmes. It is very warm.\a148\a147Good old Watson! You are the one fixed point in a changing age. There\a146s an east wind coming all the same, such a wind as never blew on England yet. It will be cold and bitter, Watson and a good many of us may wither before its blast. But it\a146s God\a146s own wind none the less, and a cleaner, better, stronger land will lie in the sunshine when the storm has cleared. Start her up, Watson, for it\a146s time that we were on our way. I have a cheque for five hundred pounds which should be cashed early, for the drawer is quite capable of stopping it if he can.\a148\p\c\l\X0\BThe Valley Of Fear\B\X0\BBy Sir Arthur Conan Doyle\B\l\p\i\m="vall-15c.png"\i\c\p\X1\c\BPart 1 - The Tragedy of Birlstone\B\X1\c\BChapter 1\B - \X2\BThe Warning\B\X2\a147I am inclined to think\a151\a148 said I.\a147I should do so,\a148 Sherlock Holmes remarked impatiently.I believe that I am one of the most long-suffering of mortals; but I\a146ll admit that I was annoyed at the sardonic interruption. \a147Really, Holmes,\a148 said I severely, \a147you are a little trying at times.\a148He was too much absorbed with his own thoughts to give any immediate answer to my remonstrance. He leaned upon his hand, with his untasted breakfast before him, and he stared at the slip of paper which he had just drawn from its envelope. Then he took the envelope itself, held it up to the light, and very carefully studied both the exterior and the flap.\a147It is Porlock\a146s writing,\a148 said he thoughtfully. \a147I can hardly doubt that it is Porlock\a146s writing, though I have seen it only twice before. The Greek e with the peculiar top flourish is distinctive. But if it is Porlock, then it must be something of the very first importance.\a148He was speaking to himself rather than to me; but my vexation disappeared in the interest which the words awakened.\a147Who then is Porlock?\a148 I asked.\a147Porlock, Watson, is a \inom-de-plume\i, a mere identification mark; but behind it lies a shifty and evasive personality. In a former letter he frankly informed me that the name was not his own, and defied me ever to trace him among the teeming millions of this great city. Porlock is important, not for himself, but for the great man with whom he is in touch. Picture to yourself the pilot fish with the shark, the jackal with the lion\a151 anything that is insignificant in companionship with what is formidable: not only formidable, Watson, but sinister\a151 in the highest degree sinister. That is where he comes within my purview. You have heard me speak of Professor Moriarty?\a148\a147The famous scientific criminal, as famous among crooks as\a151\a148\a147My blushes, Watson!\a148 Holmes murmured in a deprecating voice.\a147I was about to say, as he is unknown to the public.\a148\a147A touch\a151 a distinct touch!\a148 cried Holmes. \a147You are developing a certain unexpected vein of pawky humour, Watson, against which I must learn to guard myself. But in calling Moriarty a criminal you are uttering libel in the eyes of the law\a151 and there lie the glory and the wonder of it. The greatest schemer of all time, the organizer of every devilry, the controlling brain of the underworld, a brain which might have made or marred the destiny of nations\a151 that\a146s the man. But so aloof is he from general suspicion, so immune from criticism, so admirable in his management and self-effacement, that for those very words that you have uttered he could hale you to a court and emerge with your year\a146s pension as a solatium for his wounded character. Is he not the celebrated author of \iThe Dynamics of an Asteroid\i, a book which ascends to such rarefied heights of pure mathematics that it is said that there was no man in the scientific press capable of criticizing it. Is this a man to traduce? Foul-mouthed doctor and slandered professor\a151 such would be your respective \ir\a244les\i. That\a146s genius, Watson. But if I am spared by lesser men, our day will surely come.\a148\a147May I be there to see!\a148 I exclaimed devoutly. \a147But you were speaking of this man Porlock.\a148\a147Ah, yes\a151 the so-called Porlock is a link in the chain some little way from its great attachment. Porlock is not quite a sound link\a151 between ourselves. He is the only flaw in that chain so far as I have been able to test it.\a148\a147But no chain is stronger than its weakest link.\a148\a147Exactly, my dear Watson. Hence the extreme importance of Porlock. Led on by some rudimentary aspirations towards right, and encouraged by the judicious stimulation of an occasional ten-pound note sent to him by devious methods, he has once or twice given me advance information which has been of value\a151 that highest value which anticipates and prevents rather than avenges crime. I cannot doubt that, if we had the cipher, we should find that this communication is of the nature that I indicate.\a148Again Holmes flattened out the paper upon his unused plate. I rose and, leaning over him, stared down at the curious inscription, which ran as follows:534 C2 13 127 36 31 4 17 21 41 DOUGLAS 109 293 5 37 BIRLSTONE 26 BIRLSTONE 9 47 171\a147What do you make of it, Holmes?\a148\a147It is obviously an attempt to convey secret information.\a148\a147But what is the use of a cipher message without the cipher?\a148\a147In this instance, none at all.\a148\a147Why do you say \a145in this instance\a146?\a148\a147Because there are many ciphers which I would read as easily as I do the apocrypha of the agony column: such crude devices amuse the intelligence without fatiguing it. But this is different. It is clearly a reference to the words in a page of some book. Until I am told which page and which book I am powerless.\a148\a147But why \a145Douglas\a146 and \a145Birlstone\a146?\a148\a147Clearly because those are words which were not contained in the page in question.\a148\a147Then why has he not indicated the book?\a148\a147Your native shrewdness, my dear Watson, that innate cunning which is the delight of your friends, would surely prevent you from inclosing cipher and message in the same envelope. Should it miscarry, you are undone. As it is, both have to go wrong before any harm comes from it. Our second post is now overdue, and I shall be surprised if it does not bring us either a further letter of explanation, or, as is more probable, the very volume to which these figures refer.\a148Holmes\a146s calculation was fulfilled within a very few minutes by the appearance of Billy, the page, with the very letter which we were expecting.\a147The same writing,\a148 remarked Holmes, as he opened the envelope, \a147and actually signed,\a148 he added in an exultant voice as he unfolded the epistle. \a147Come, we are getting on, Watson.\a148 His brow clouded, however, as he glanced over the contents.\a147Dear me, this is very disappointing. I fear, Watson, that all our expectations come to nothing. I trust that the man Porlock will come to no harm.\a147DEAR MR. HOLMES [he says]:\a147I will go no further in this matter. It is too dangerous\a151 he suspects me. I can see that he suspects me. He came to me quite unexpectedly after I had actually addressed this envelope with the intention of sending you the key to the cipher. I was able to cover it up. If he had seen it, it would have gone hard with me. But I read suspicion in his eyes. Please burn the cipher message, which can now be of no use to you.FRED PORLOCK.\a148Holmes sat for some little time twisting this letter between his fingers, and frowning, as he stared into the fire.\a147After all,\a148 he said at last, \a147there may be nothing in it. It may be only his guilty conscience. Knowing himself to be a traitor, he may have read the accusation in the other\a146s eyes.\a148\a147The other being, I presume, Professor Moriarty.\a148\a147No less. When any of that party talk about \a145He\a146 you know whom they mean. There is one predominant \a145He\a146 for all of them.\a148\a147But what can he do?\a148\a147Hum. That\a146s a large question. When you have one of the first brains of Europe up against you, and all the powers of darkness at his back, there are infinite possibilities. Anyhow, Friend Porlock is evidently scared out of his senses\a151 kindly compare the writing in the note to that upon its envelope; which was done, he tells us, before this ill-omened visit. The one is clear and firm. The other hardly legible.\a148\a147Why did he write at all. Why did he not simply drop it?\a148\a147Because he feared I would make some inquiry after him in that case, and possibly bring trouble on him.\a148\a147No doubt,\a148 said I. \a147Of course.\a148 I had picked up the original cipher message and was bending my brows over it. \a147It\a146s pretty maddening to think that an important secret may lie here on this slip of paper, and that it is beyond human power to penetrate it.\a148Sherlock Holmes had pushed away his untasted breakfast and lit the unsavoury pipe which was the companion of his deepest meditations. \a147I wonder!\a148 said he, leaning back and staring at the ceiling. \a147Perhaps there are points which have escaped your Machiavellian intellect. Let us consider the problem in the light of pure reason. This man\a146s reference is to a book. That is our point of departure.\a148\a147A somewhat vague one.\a148\a147Let us see then if we can narrow it down. As I focus my mind upon it, it seems rather less impenetrable. What indications have we as to this book?\a148\a147None.\a148\a147Well, well, it is surely not quite so bad as that. The cipher message begins with a large 534, does it not. We may take it as a working hypothesis that 534 is the particular page to which the cipher refers. So our book has already become a \ilarge\i book, wh