oned fireplace with an iron screen behind it dated 1670, there blazed and spluttered a splendid log fire.The room, as I gazed round, was a most singular mixture of dates and of places. The half-panelled walls may well have belonged to the original yeoman farmer of the seventeenth century. They were ornamented, however, on the lower part by a line of well-chosen modern water-colours; while above, where yellow plaster took the place of oak, there was hung a fine collection of South American utensils and weapons, which had been brought, no doubt, by the Peruvian lady upstairs. Holmes rose, with that quick curiosity which sprang from his eager mind, and examined them with some care. He returned with his eyes full of thought.\a147Hullo!\a148 he cried. \a147Hullo!\a148A spaniel had lain in a basket in the corner. It came slowly forward towards its master, walking with difficulty. Its hind legs moved irregularly and its tail was on the ground. It licked Ferguson\a146s hand.\a147What is it, Mr. Holmes?\a148\a147The dog. What\a146s the matter with it?\a148\a147That\a146s what puzzled the vet. A sort of paralysis. Spinal meningitis, he thought. But it is passing. He\a146ll be all right soon\a151 won\a146t you, Carlo?\a148A shiver of assent passed through the drooping tail. The dog\a146s mournful eyes passed from one of us to the other. He knew that we were discussing his case.\a147Did it come on suddenly?\a148\a147In a single night.\a148\a147How long ago?\a148\a147It may have been four months ago.\a148\a147Very remarkable. Very suggestive.\a148\a147What do you see in it, Mr. Holmes?\a148\a147A confirmation of what I had already thought.\a148\a147For God\a146s sake, what do you think, Mr. Holmes? It may be a mere intellectual puzzle to you, but it is life and death to me! My wife a would-be murderer\a151 my child in constant danger! Don\a146t play with me, Mr. Holmes. It is too terribly serious.\a148The big Rugby three-quarter was trembling all 