ssuring words, and she lay still while I took her pulse and temperature. Both were high, and yet my impression was that the condition was rather that of mental and nervous excitement than of any actual seizure.\a147She lie like that one day, two day. I \a146fraid she die,\a148 said the girl.The woman turned her flushed and handsome face towards me.\a147Where is my husband?\a148\a147He is below and would wish to see you.\a148\a147I will not see him. I will not see him.\a148 Then she seemed to wander off into delirium. \a147A fiend! A fiend! Oh, what shall I do with this devil?\a148\a147Can I help you in any way?\a148\a147No. No one can help. It is finished. All is destroyed. Do what I will, all is destroyed.\a148The woman must have some strange delusion. I could not see honest Bob Ferguson in the character of fiend or devil.\a147Madame,\a148 I said, \a147your husband loves you dearly. He is deeply grieved at this happening.\a148Again she turned on me those glorious eyes.\a147He loves me. Yes. But do I not love him? Do I not love him even to sacrifice myself rather than break his dear heart? That is how I love him. And yet he could think of me\a151 he could speak of me so.\a148\a147He is full of grief, but he cannot understand.\a148\a147No, he cannot understand. But he should trust.\a148\a147Will you not see him?\a148 I suggested.\a147No, no, I cannot forget those terrible words nor the look upon his face. I will not see him. Go now. You can do nothing for me. Tell him only one thing. I want my child. I have a right to my child. That is the only message I can send him.\a148 She turned her face to the wall and would say no more.I returned to the room downstairs, where Ferguson and Holmes still sat by the fire. Ferguson listened moodily to my account of the interview.\a147How can I send her the child?\a148 he said. \a147How do I know what strange impulse might come upon her? How can I ever forget how she rose from beside it with its blood upon her lips?\a148 He shuddered at the recollection. \a147The child is safe with Mrs. Mason, and there he must remain.\a148A smart maid, the only modern thing which we had seen in the house, had brought in some tea. As she was serving it the door opened and a youth entered the room. He was a remarkable lad, pale-faced and fair-haired, with excitable light blue eyes which blazed into a sudden flame of emotion and joy as they rested upon his father. He rushed forward and threw his arms round his neck with the abandon of a loving girl.\a147Oh, daddy,\a148 he cried, \a147I did not know that you were due yet. I should have been here to meet you. Oh, I am so glad to see you!\a148Ferguson gently disengaged himself from the embrace with some little show of embarrassment.\a147Dear old chap,\a148 said he, patting the flaxen head with a very tender hand. \a147I came early because my friends, Mr. Holmes and Dr. Watson, have been persuaded to come down and spend an evening with us.\a148\a147Is that Mr. Holmes, the detective?\a148\a147Yes.\a148The youth looked at us with a very penetrating and, as it seemed to me, unfriendly gaze.\a147What about your other child, Mr. Ferguson?\a148 asked Holmes. \a147Might we make the acquaintance of the baby?\a148\a147Ask Mrs. Mason to bring baby down,\a148 said Ferguson. The boy went off with a curious, shambling gait which told my surgical eyes that he was suffering from a weak spine. Presently he returned, and behind him came a tall, gaunt woman bearing in her arms a very beautiful child, dark-eyed, golden-haired, a wonderful mixture of the Saxon and the Latin. Ferguson was evidently devoted to it, for he took it into his arms and fondled it most tenderly.\a147Fancy anyone having the heart to hurt him,\a148 he muttered as he glanced down at the small, angry red pucker upon the cherub throat.It was at this moment that I chanced to glance at Holmes and saw a most singular intentness in his expression. His face was as set as if it had been carved out of old ivory, and his eyes, which had glanced for a moment at father and child, were now fixed with eager curiosity upon something at the other side of the room. Following his gaze I could only guess that he was looking out through the window at the melancholy, dripping garden. It is true that a shutter had half closed outside and obstructed the view, but none the less it was certainly at the window that Holmes was fixing his concentrated attention. Then he smiled, and his eyes came back to the baby. On its chubby neck there was this small puckered mark. Without speaking, Holmes examined it with care. Finally he shook one of the dimpled fists which waved in front of him.\a147Good-bye, little man. You have made a strange start in life. Nurse, I should wish to have a word with you in private.\a148He took her aside and spoke earnestly for a few minutes. I only heard the last words, which were: \a147Your anxiety will soon, I hope, be set at rest.\a148 The woman, who seemed to be a sour, silent kind of creature, withdrew with the child.\a147What is Mrs. Mason like?\a148 asked Holmes.\a147Not very prepossessing externally, as you can see, but a heart of gold, and devoted to the child.\a148\a147Do you like her, Jack?\a148 Holmes turned suddenly upon the boy. His expressive mobile face shadowed over, and he shook his head.\a147Jacky has very strong likes and dislikes,\a148 said Ferguson, putting his arm round the boy. \a147Luckily I am one of his likes.\a148The boy cooed and nestled his head upon his father\a146s breast. Ferguson gently disengaged him.\a147Run away, little Jacky,\a148 said he, and he watched his son with loving eyes until he disappeared. \a147Now, Mr. Holmes,\a148 he continued when the boy was gone, \a147I really feel that I have brought you on a fool\a146s errand, for what can you possibly do save give me your sympathy? It must be an exceedingly delicate and complex affair from your point of view.\a148\a147It is certainly delicate,\a148 said my friend with an amused smile, \a147but I have not been struck up to now with its complexity. It has been a case for intellectual deduction, but when this original intellectual deduction is confirmed point by point by quite a number of independent incidents, then the subjective becomes objective and we can say confidently that we have reached our goal. I had, in fact, reached it before we left Baker Street, and the rest has merely been observation and confirmation.\a148Ferguson put his big hand to his furrowed forehead.\a147For heaven\a146s sake, Holmes,\a148 he said hoarsely; \a147if you can see the truth in this matter, do not keep me in suspense. How do I stand? What shall I do? I care nothing as to how you have found your facts so long as you have really got them.\a148\a147Certainly I owe you an explanation, and you shall have it. But you will permit me to handle the matter in my own way? Is the lady capable of seeing us, Watson?\a148\a147She is ill, but she is quite rational.\a148\a147Very good. It is only in her presence that we can clear the matter up. Let us go up to her.\a148\a147She will not see me,\a148 cried Ferguson.\a147Oh, yes, she will,\a148 said Holmes. He scribbled a few lines upon a sheet of paper.\a147You at least have the entree, Watson. Will you have the goodness to give the lady this note?\a148I ascended again and handed the note to Dolores, who cautiously opened the door. A minute later I heard a cry from within, a cry in which joy and surprise seemed to be blended. Dolores looked out.\a147She will see them. She will leesten,\a148 said she.At my summons Ferguson and Holmes came up. As we entered the room Ferguson took a step or two towards his wife, who had raised herself in the bed, but she held out her hand to repulse him. He sank into an armchair, while Holmes seated himself beside him, after bowing to the lady, who looked at him with wide-eyed amazement.\a147I think we can dispense with Dolores,\a148 said Holmes. \a147Oh, very well, madame, if you would rather she stayed I can see no objection. Now, Mr. Ferguson, I am a busy man with many calls, and my methods have to be short and direct. The swiftest surgery is the least painful. Let me first say what will ease your mind. Your wife is a very good, a very loving, and a very ill-used woman.\a148Ferguson sat up with a cry of joy.\a147Prove that, Mr. Holmes, and I am your debtor forever.\a148\a147I will do so, but in doing so I must wound you deeply in another direction.\a148\a147I care nothing so long as you clear my wife. Everything on earth is insignificant compared to that.\a148\a147Let me tell you, then, the train of reasoning which passed through my mind in Baker Street. The idea of a vampire was to me absurd. Such things do not happen in criminal practice in England. And yet your observation was precise. You had seen the lady rise from beside the child\a146s cot with the blood upon her lips.\a148\a147I did.\a148\a147Did it not occur to you that a bleeding wound may be sucked for some other purpose than to draw the blood from it? Was there not a queen in English history who sucked such a wound to draw poison from it?\a148\a147Poison!\a148\a147A South American household. My instinct felt the presence of those weapons upon the wall before my eyes ever saw them. It might have been other poison, but that was what occurred to me. When I saw that little empty quiver beside the small birdbow, it was just what I expected to see. If the child were pricked with one of those arrows dipped in curare or some other devilish drug, it would mean death if the venom were not sucked out.\a147And the dog! If one were to use such a poison, would one not try it first in order to see that it had not lost its power? I did not foresee the dog, but at least I understand him and he fitted into my reconstruction.\a147Now do you understand? Your wife feared such an attack. She saw it made and saved the child\a146s life, and yet she shrank from telling you all the truth, for she knew how you loved the boy and feared lest it break your heart.\a148\a147Jacky!\a148\a147I watched him as you fondled the child just now. His face was clearly reflected in the glass of the window where the shutter formed a background. I saw such jealousy, such cruel hatred, as I have seldom seen in a human face.\a148\a147My Jacky!\a148\a147You have to face it, Mr. Ferguson. It is the more painful because it is a distorted love, a maniacal exaggerated love for you, and possibly for his dead mother, which has prompted his action. His very soul is consumed with hatred for this splendid child, whose health and beauty are a contrast to his own weakness.\a148\a147Good God! It is incredible!\a148\a147Have I spoken the truth, madame?\a148The lady was sobbing, with her face buried in the pillows. Now she turned to her husband.\a147How could I tell you, Bob? I felt the blow it would be to you. It was better that I should wait and that it should come from some other lips than mine. When this gentleman, who seems to have powers of magic, wrote that he knew all, I was glad.\a148\a147I think a year at sea would be my prescription for Master Jacky,\a148 said Holmes, rising from his chair. \a147Only one thing is still clouded, madame. We can quite understand your attacks upon Master Jacky. There is a limit to a mother\a146s patience. But how did you dare to leave the child these last two days?\a148\a147I had told Mrs. Mason. She knew.\a148\a147Exactly. So I imagined.\a148Ferguson was standing by the bed, choking, his hands outstretched and quivering.\a147This, I fancy, is the time for our exit, Watson,\a148 said Holmes in a whisper. \a147If you will take one elbow of the too faithful Dolores, I will take the other. There, now,\a148 he added as he closed the door behind him, \a147I think we may leave them to settle the rest among themselves.\a148I have only one further note of this case. It is the letter which Holmes wrote in final answer to that with which the narrative begins. It ran thus:BAKER STREET,Nov. 21st.Re VampiresSIR:Referring to your letter of the 19th, I beg to state that I have looked into the inquiry of your client, Mr. Robert Ferguson, of Ferguson and Muirhead, tea brokers, of Mincing Lane, and that the matter has been brought to a satisfactory conclusion. With thanks for your recommendation, I am, sir,Faithfully yours,SHERLOCK HOLMES.\p\X1\BThe Three Garridebs\B\X1\c\i\m="3gar-04.png"\i\cIt may have been a comedy, or it may have been a tragedy. It cost one man his reason, it cost me a blood-letting, and it cost yet another man the penalties of the law. Yet there was certainly an element of comedy. Well, you shall judge for yourselves.I remember the date very well, for it was in the same month that Holmes refused a knighthood for services which may perhaps some day be described. I only refer to the matter in passing, for in my position of partner and confidant I am obliged to be particularly careful to avoid any indiscretion. I repeat, however, that this enables me to fix the date, which was the latter end of June, 1902, shortly after the conclusion of the South African War. Holmes had spent several days in bed, as was his habit from time to time, but he emerged that morning with a long foolscap document in his hand and a twinkle of amusement in his austere gray eyes.\a147There is a chance for you to make some money, friend Watson,\a148 said he. \a147Have you ever heard the name of Garrideb?\a148I admitted that I had not.\a147Well, if you can lay your hand upon a Garrideb, there\a146s money in it.\a148\a147Why?\a148\a147Ah, that\a146s a long story\a151 rather a whimsical one, too. I don\a146t think in all our explorations of human complexities we have ever come upon anything more singular. The fellow will be here presently for cross-examination, so I won\a146t open the matter up till he comes. But, meanwhile, that\a146s the name we want.\a148The telephone directory lay on the table beside me, and I turned over the pages in a rather hopeless quest. But to my amazement there was this strange name in its due place. I gave a cry of triumph.\a147Here you are, Holmes! Here it is!\a148Holmes took the book from my hand.\a147\a160\a145Garrideb, N.,\a146 \a147 he read, \a147\a160\a145136 Little Ryder Street, W.\a146 Sorry to disappoint you, my dear Watson, but this is the man himself. That is the address upon his letter. We want another to match him.\a148Mrs. Hudson had come in with a card upon a tray. I took it up and glanced at it.\a147Why, here it is!\a148 I cried in amazement. \a147This is a different initial. John Garrideb, Counsellor at Law, Moorville, Kansas, U. S. A. \a148Holmes smiled as he looked at the card. \a147I am afraid you must make yet another effort, Watson,\a148 said he. \a147This gentleman is also in the plot already, though I certainly did not expect to see him this morning. However, he is in a position to tell us a good deal which I want to know.\a148A moment later he was in the room. Mr. John Garrideb, Counsellor at Law, was a short, powerful man with the round, fresh, clean-shaven face characteristic of so many American men of affairs. The general effect was chubby and rather childlike, so that one received the impression of quite a young man with a broad set smile upon his face. His eyes, however, were arresting. Seldom in any human head have I seen a pair which bespoke a more intense inward life, so bright were they, so alert, so responsive to every change of thought. His accent was American, but was not accompanied by any eccentricity of speech.\a147Mr. Holmes?\a148 he asked, glancing from one to the other. \a147Ah, yes! Your pictures are not unlike you, sir, if I may say so. I believe you have had a letter from my namesake, Mr. Nathan Garrideb, have you not?\a148\a147Pray sit down,\a148 said Sherlock Holmes. \a147We shall, I fancy, have a good deal to discuss.\a148 He took up his sheets of foolscap. \a147You are, of course, the Mr. John Garrideb mentioned in this document. But surely you have been in England some time?\a148\a147Why do you say that, Mr. Holmes?\a148 I seemed to read sudden suspicion in those expressive eyes.\a147Your whole outfit is English.\a148Mr. Garrideb forced a laugh. \a147I\a146ve read of your tricks, Mr. Holmes, but I never thought I would be the subject of them. Where do you read that?\a148\a147The shoulder cut of your coat, the toes of your boots\a151 could anyone doubt it?\a148\a147Well, well, I had no idea I was so obvious a Britisher. But business brought me over here some time ago, and so, as you say, my outfit is nearly all London. However, I guess your time is of value, and we did not meet to talk about the cut of my socks. What about getting down to that paper you hold in your hand?\a148Holmes had in some way ruffled our visitor, whose chubby face had assumed a far less amiable expression.\a147Patience! Patience, Mr. Garrideb!\a148 said my friend in a soothing voice. \a147Dr. Watson would tell you that these little digressions of mine sometimes prove in the end to have some bearing on the matter. But why did Mr. Nathan Garrideb not come with you?\a148\a147Why did he ever drag you into it at all?\a148 asked our visitor with a sudden outflame of anger. \a147What in thunder had you to do with it? Here was a bit of professional business between two gentlemen, and one of them must needs call in a detective! I saw him this morning, and he told me this fool-trick he had played me, and that\a146s why I am here. But I feel bad about it, all the same.\a148\a147There was no reflection upon you, Mr. Garrideb. It was simply zeal upon his part to gain your end\a151 an end which is, I understand, equally vital for both of you. He knew that I had means of getting information, and, therefore, it was very natural that he should apply to me.\a148Our visitor\a146s angry face gradually cleared.\a147Well, that puts it different,\a148 said he. \a147When I went to see him this morning and he told me he had sent to a detective, I just asked for your address and came right away. I don\a146t want police butting into a private matter. But if you are content just to help us find the man, there can be no harm in that.\a148\a147Well, that is just how it stands,\a148 said Holmes. \a147And now, sir, since you are here, we had best have a clear account from your own lips. My friend here knows nothing of the details.\a148Mr. Garrideb surveyed me with not too friendly a gaze.\a147Need he know?\a148 he asked.\a147We usually work together.\a148\a147Well, there\a146s no reason it should be kept a secret. I\a146ll give you the facts as short as I can make them. If you came from Kansas I would not need to explain to you who Alexander Hamilton Garrideb was. He made his money in real estate, and afterwards in the wheat pit at Chicago, but he spent it in buying up as much land as would make one of your counties, lying along the Arkansas River, west of Fort Dodge. It\a146s grazing-land and lumber-land and arable-land and mineralized-land, and just every sort of land that brings dollars to the man that owns it.\a147He had no kith nor kin\a151 or, if he had, I never heard of it. But he took a kind of pride in the queerness of his name. That was what brought us together. I was in the law at Topeka, and one day I had a visit from the old man, and he was tickled to death to meet another man with his own name. It was his pet fad, and he was dead set to find out if there were any more Garridebs in the world. \a145Find me another!\a146 said he. I told him I was a busy man and could not spend my life hiking round the world in search of Garridebs. \a145None the less,\a146 said he, \a145that is just what you will do if things pan out as I planned them.\a146 I thought he was joking, but there was a powerful lot of meaning